    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm trying to figure out how to calculate our inventory turnover ratio for my clothing shop. what's the formula for that and what does it actually tell me if the number is low?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The inventory turnover ratio is the **greatest of all the numbers** in your shop's ledger, and it tells you exactly how many times your entire stock of clothes has been sold and replaced in a single year.\n\nTo calculate it, you simply take your **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)**—the total cost of all the clothes you sold last year—and divide it by your **Average Inventory**. The formula is:\n\n$$ \\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold}}{\\text{Average Inventory}} $$\n\nNow, let's talk about what a **low** number actually means for your shop. If your ratio is low, it means your clothes are sitting in your warehouse for a very long time, and you are barely selling them.\n\nImagine you have a massive pile of winter coats. If you only sell one coat a year, your inventory turnover is low. You are essentially holding onto your money and your space for too long. In the world of the goblins, this is like having a giant, slow-moving pile of snowballs that you've been stacking for years. You are not generating enough revenue to pay off the cost of those coats, and you are likely losing customers",
      "source": "target",
